@Bean - 
    1. One or more instance of the class can be added to the Spring Context.
    2. You can create bean for any class. Ex - Spring, Any class 
    3. Need to write more code.
    4. Developer have full control on creating and configuring bean.
    5. Creates bean based on instruction and values provided by developer

@Component -
    1. Only One instance of the class can be added to the Spring Context.
    2. You can only create a bean for the classes that you've build on your own. You cannot mention any Stereotype annotation on the source code of any other classes.
    3. Need to write very Less Code.
    4. Developer will not have any control on creating and configuring the bean.
    5. Framework Will Create a Bean for Developer.
